text: Absolutely delicious food. A little run down but cozy atmosphere. No wait.

name: Gwyneth Rose
text: I can't say enough good things about this place. After walking by it a million times, I finally decided to go here with some friends. The chicken souvlaki was juicy and perfectly spiced, plus the pita it was wrapped in was everything a pita should be. The baklava was just fantastic- all sorts of spices, not too sweet and made with wonderfully flaky philo dough. On top of all that, the service was just wonderful. The owner of the place is just super attentive and friendly- we ended up having a nice little conversation over the baklava, and, again, this was the first time we'd ever been there. So, yeah, this place is pretty great.

name: Rich Allen
text: This is a great place. They treat me like family. Amazing food and great prices.

name: Patrick Garofallou
text: This place is great! Mini (the owner) is very friendly and welcoming and the food is always excellent.

name: Vanessa Watson
text: My boyfriend and I came in an hour before closing and still got delicious, fresh food and great service! The owner chatted with us while we ate and was super sweet. We had pita & tzatziki as an appetizer - BEST tzatziki either of us has ever had! I had the mousaka, and my boyfriend had a beef & lamb gyro - both equally fantastic! I had the Greek coffee - perfectly thick and so so tasty. And of course we had to have the baklava for dessert, and just like everything else, it was absolutely mouthwatering! Definitely repeat customers here!! Satisfied my Greek food craving and then some!

name: Karissa Swanson
text: We were greeted enthusiastically and offered many options for "made-from-scratch" meals. We ordered the mousaka, falafel, and hummus & pita. All of the dishes were freshly prepared and full of flavor. This was the best falafel I've had, not like the dry fried balls you get at most places. We had to try the baklava- it was fresh from the oven- and it was amazing. Highly recommend this place!!

text: Fast friendly service and quality food. I have only eaten Indian cuisine a couple times now, but was very impressed by the food I ordered here. Tofu korma was a sweet, creamy, and slightly spicy sauce and the side of Channa masala was equally as good. I will definitely be going back

It was still decent and probably a good place to hit for lunch or a quick bite to eat at dinner time.

text: I love this place! It's like the Subway of Indian food. I love watching my bowl being made and all the options I have. You don't even have to get a bowl; you can get a plate that separates the food, a wrap, salad, and even kids meals. The staff is also friendly and extremely helpful.

name: Iean Isakson
text: I went to Taja Indian for the first time today and it was great! Super casual and relaxed atmosphere, plus the employees were friendly but not cloying. Less than $10 for any meal on the menu incl. a side of rice. I found that it was super filling. As a student who doesn't always have time to get breakfast, this place seriously hit the spot after class. The lamb curry and aloo gobi were both phenomenal. Only thing is, their spicy spice isn't spicy enough. Give the place a visit for crying out loud!

text: I really liked Bombay Bowl,  but Taja,  the place that replaced it is a pit.  It's terrible food,  with not as many options. I'll never go back.

text: Too warm in the restaurant was our first response. Noisy in the place so I had trouble hearing some of the options but the friendly girl on the counter repeated to be sure she heard correctly which I appreciated. If she hadn't, I would have missed the saag. I was happy that I didn't miss the saag! Otherwise, the food was okay, not great, but I will be back.

text: Lamb tikka was chewy and unedible. Nan was edible. Chicken tikka was okay, gut rice was horrible. Service was excellent-I wished I liked the food better!!Waste of money.

name: Nick Wulf
text: Was a huge fan of Bombay Bowl.  Decided to try the restaurant that replaced it.  Tried the tofu tikka masala - tofu had not been cooked.  No simosa rolls at the new establishment, or even simosas.  Sampled my friends saag paneer,  safe to say all 3 vegetarian options are a poor substitute for the Bombay bowl I knew and loved.

name: Brian Thomson
text: I had the chicken wrap, a side order of naan and a mango lassi. The chicken wrap was ok, just some cubed chick with sauce and maybe 4 tiny pieces of pickled onion. Maybe I have become too accustomed to Chipotle where a burrito feels like a real meal. The chicken wrap was reasonable tasty but I felt like I wanted more of a complete meal. When I asked for some vegetables or lentils to be added, the manager said that is not how it is served in India and they do not serve it that way here! The naan was practically raw dough. I asked the manager whether they are supposed to grill it before serving it and he said so and explained that maybe the dough just had too much water in it. This does not explain why parts of it were raw! The mango lassi was the standard drink you get in any Indian restaurant (I suspect that it all comes canned from one supplier). I will not be going back to Bombay Bowl again.

name: sankar das
text:
Not worth for the money.They used to provide much better quantities,nutrients while they were at the Arapahoe road and I became a lover.The photo of the bowl shows upto the neck on their website, But what you will get is barely upto to the 50% mark of their bowl even with veggies. And now veggies, Lentil cost extra money.  So, your basically eating only chicken & rice & one gravy, which is extremely less in quantity,And not like Indian standard eating, you will always be hungry, Even if you add veggies paying extra money.
In authentic Indian food lentil,raita (Yogurt) & sauces has No/zero value,And you can never ask for money for serving a spoonful of raita or lentil in India,That will look super cheap in India.But in the US everyone does. But that's not real Indian culture,I think one should First promote the culture then only can promote foods.Indians are placed at the top for hospitality,not for ripping off people for a tiny bowl of blue cheese like the wing stop.
I will always always prefer Steve's Chipotle over this for the quantity & quality they provide for that price specially the fajita & the beans and everything for no additional cost.And it fills me up real tight,Thanks to their proteins & nutrients.

name: Adam Sattley
text:
Bistro Barbes

Summary: truly a unique, hidden gem! Who would have guessed we have a North African inspired modern French restaurant in Park Hill? And it's been here for four years!

Location/Parking: Park Hill, near Elm and 26th Street. Street parking only.

Ambiance: small and narrow; nothing too fancy; elements of North African culture.

Service: top notch! A very high-level that you would expect at the most expensive French restaurants.

Cocktails: we tried a house drink made from spiced cranberry shrub and ginger beer.  It contained the spice called fenugreek. It was very exotic. It set the tone for the evening.

Amuse-bouche: complimentary, ever-changing. Ours was tasty.

Appetizers: we selected the beef cheeks. They were extremely rich, but paired nicely with a more sweet and tangy coleslaw mix.

Salads: we split the shaved pear salad as an appetizer as well. It came over a bed of brie cream and figs, topped with a red wine-cacao gastrique.

Entrees: they were out of duck leg, so they informed us they would be substituting it for duck breast. Toni and I still ordered the duck, and it was cooked to perfection! It was set atop of saffron basmati rice, roasted brussel sprouts, and butternut squash chips. Bob ordered the hanger steak. It looked amazing! It was served with raclette over a bed of kale. I tasted some of the steak and it was really delicious.

Desserts: we had been warned that the desserts are fairly small, but we still decided just to split one dessert among the three of us. It was perfect. We ordered the chocolate hazelnut creme brulee. It was definitely a different take on this traditional dessert, as it did not come in a ramiken, but was served over a pool of rosewater-infused white chocolate with supremed orange segments, and petit meringue cookies.

All in all, this was a great experience! I highly recommend checking it out. We visited on the Thursday night before Christmas and it was very slow. Hopefully they get much more business soon!

name: Janet Dybek
text:
The food here is amazing. Service impeccable. It's a cozy set up. It's about eight total table with one high top closer to the open kitchen.

I had the Pei Mussels for appetizer. The garlic chive sausage, padron Chili's, leeks, Dijon-paprika brodo was a perfect harmony of smell and unforgettable surprise for my palette. The broth. Above average in taste. Served with fresh baked bread. Once you dip that bread you're hooked. I swear I almost didn't go beyond the appetizer. I just wanted more of that mussels. When the waiter came to clear the plate for my next dish I had to restrain myself from stopping him.

The shaved Bartlett Pears came next. My aversion to sweet entree, salad or anything else that's not desert was totally squashed here. The Marcona Almond vinaigrette, black mission figs, Brie crema , red wine-cacao gastrique all worked in perfect harmony to produce an end result that was perfectly in sync.

I chose the Hanger Steak for my entree since a couple of nights ago I had an amazing fish dinner. I'm mostly a meat eater. I know my meat. I am in awe of this entree. Super tender to start with. Perfectly cooked as requested medium. Pink and so enticing. The streak sat on top of sweet potato raclette aligot, sautéed kale, Moroccan roasted carrots, red wine-sage jus. Amen!
(P.S Aligot is made from mashed potatoes blended with butter, cream, crushed garlic, and melted cheese.)

I had their old fashion to keep me a bit distracted and I went home enchanted.

And that creme brûlée....

This is an off the beaten path location that is perfect for a date night with a special someone. Keep your mind open about the location. Bear in mind you're here for the food. You won't be sorry.

name: frank p.
text: Quality ingredients and care in preparation. Very impressed. We did not have any of the vegan options, but intend to try them the next go around. We ordered from UberEats on a Sunday evening, for whatever reason my experience trying new-to-me restaurants at the end of a weekend has not been good via Uber. This was not the case here. When trying a new pizza spot, we tend to order the basics. If they can nail the basics, then it's likely that everything else will be done well too. We ordered the pepperoni and breadsticks with a side of pizza sauce for dipping. Wow. The pizza toppings were perfectly dispersed, a nice amount of slightly spicy red sauce, hand-tossed crust leaning toward the thin crust side (good thing), pepperonis were slightly crispy, the cheese blend and sprinkled seasoning evenly spread, all perfectly cooked, and cut appropriately. The breadsticks were a bit fluffy, flavorful on their own, and paired well with a slightly spicier pizza sauce for dipping. Job well done. We are always looking for that traditionally done pizza concept place done right. We found it.

My only complaint (and not worth demerits) is the pricing. We have not tried any of the specialty vegan pizzas due to the high pricing. If the pizzas were offered at a more competitive rate, we likely would venture out past the cheese pizza. Unfortunately, we have noticed other vegan options here are raising in pricing. I hope this is not a trend as we may have to stop visiting as regularly! Either way, I am grateful to have them as an option. Thank you T-Mama's for offering vegan items!

name: Adam Sattley
text:
Noble Riot a trendy winebar making a lot of noise in the Denver foodie scene.  Ironically, they don't even have a kitchen.

Prepare yourselves by having great customer service from start to finish.  Everyone we encountered seemed truly genuine in creating a pleasant experience.

Our server, Michael S., seemed very passionate about our questions surrounding "orange wine".  He explained that it is a term for skin-contacted white wine,  where the grape skins are not removed in the fermenting process.  He recommended a very reasonably priced bottle that paired exceptionally well with our chicken sandwich meals. Chicken sandwiches and orange wine!?! Welcome to RiNo. 😘

Food on the menu actually comes from the kitchen of the jazz club, Nocturne, located next door.  Their buckets of fried chicken are getting rave reviews, but mostly consist of dark meat.  Michael thought that we would actually really enjoy the unique chicken sandwiches, and he was right!  The light breading on the crispy chicken breast was the perfect consistency.  It paired well with the homemade bread-and-butter pickles, and house aoli. The purple fingerling fries that accompanied the sandwich completed the flavor pallet nicely.

The atmosphere could be called graffiti-chic.  The main entrance is off of the street art filled alley, just west of Larimer Street.  The décor pays respect to its industrial warehouse origin and is unapologetic in creating a comfortable atmosphere to enjoy and experience new wines.  With bottles priced as low as $30, don't let the hype hinder you from trying out this debonair find!

resp.text: Veronnica - Thanks for taking the time to share the love with this review and for having some fun exploring the blind wine option with your table. If you're ever interested in learning more about blind tasting you should check out one of our wine classes. In the meantime, we're so happy you enjoyed the food, wine, and service while at Noble Riot.

name: Janet Dybek
text:
To me Noble Riot is a star in the making. Three guys who got together to bring us mere mortals wines that are going to be unique to Coloradans. It could be wines that you’ve never heard of.

Their manifesto is awesome. Wines from good dirt and honest. I don’t about you but I’m in! I’m drinking that cool aid called The Juice in their menu. Great concept.

When you’re sitting at this cozy location just like me you might notice that they play awesome tunes overhead. It’s courtesy of one of the owners  who also owns Nocturne next door. It’s a jazz and supper club. And he’s a Sommelier as well. That’s Scott and Bowen who’s the founder of the CO Natural Wine Consortium. Both these self proclaimed geeks will be manning the Noble Riot bar nightly.

Joel Kampfe who is from the Bay Area in California is a sommelier and who curated the programs for the ENO Wine Bar Brand. He is also their education director for their upcoming Flight Club. A fun way to learn about wine.

This summer their much awaited Patio Rollout in its activated RiNo alley. You will be surrounded by hip art! This will be the best alley! Ever!

When making pizzas or finding an order, this pizza hut in particular puts whole meals on hold for up to an hour at a time, without calling to the pick up family, to explain why they are waiting up to an hour for a cold and in disarray pizza to be plopped in front if them.

I asked about the time in my confirmation email and was told "it doesn't work that way here". Then when it was finally ready I had to remind them to get all the side items I paid for.   I'll order from the Colorado Blvd location instead from now on.

text: Not open 24hrs as stated.... the sign on the door says 24hrs, but there's a trash can blocking the drive-thru. Since the lights were on and people were inside, we came in anyway as it's connected to a Pilot gas station. The interior signs were set up in front of the entrance but it looked like they were moved for cleaning. We were wrong.... When we got in line, the manager left the back and went over to move the signs to more effectively baracade the entrance and glared at us as he walked back behind the counter. There was no sign posted anywhere stating they were closing early for any reason... it was only 11:30pm. We just left a concert and were starving. It was not unreasonable to be there at that time for a "24hr" establishment!!! More people kept coming in, so he radioed for security to stop them saying he had staff on a break and was closing at midnight... Why would someone allow staff to take a break right before closing, if that were the case? I asked if it was not opened 24hrs, he used the same lame excuse....

name: Adam Sattley
text:
COVID-19 Disclaimer: The decision to dine-in during this current pandemic is important and a very personal decision that each of us must make on our own. We must accept the risks we would be taking if we were to dine out of the home, which may be smaller or greater for different individuals. This review is just something fun to read. :)

Last Sunday evening, I met Steve for an early dinner on the patio of Gattara, a relatively new Italian restaurant attached to the Warwick Hotel at the intersection of 17th and Grant.

Masks were worn by all parties until we were completely seated. We sat outside on the patio, where the closest patron was about 20 feet away.

Our waiter was named Sean, and he was great; he was very attentive. We had the choice of dining inside where we would have been extremely social-distanced from the closest neighboring patrons, or similarly spaced out on the patio. It was a beautiful afternoon, and late enough in the day that the sun was hidden by the tall buildings of downtown Denver, so we chose the patio.

According to their website, "Gattara" is the Italian equivalent of 'cat lady', without some of the negative connotations we have in America. This type of cat lady also feed stray cats in her neighborhoodand, as an endearing quality to the community.

We both ordered a signature cocktail called the Angora: Hendrick's Gin, St. Germain, white cranberry juice and fresh lemon juice. It was very cool and refreshing.

The restaurant offers Neapolitan-style pizzas that range between $12 - $18, and upscale entrees $21 - $44. However, we decided to share four appetizers $6-$16. Steve took a margherita pizza "to-go" for his other half, and it received rave reviews!

The French baguette burrata toast was delightful. It contained grana padano, arugula and tomato jam.

Steve especially liked the confit San Marzano tomato! This bruschetta was generously topped with house-made lemon ricotta and basil on a crispy focaccia bread.

The charred octopus was cooked to perfection and contained fregola, peperonata, garlic chips, radishes, and frisee. The bright red sauce under the octopus was rich and creamy.

The star of the appetizer show, and most expensive, was the smoked pork cheeks with Yukon gold gnocchi! It was served with mache and giardiniera. The pork cheeks melted right into our mouths!

Hotel restaurants can be very hit-or-miss. This one was a hit! Hopefully their business picks up, as it was pretty slow last Sunday evening. Reservations can be made via OpenTable.

name: Mile High Food Fairy
text:
Two paws up for real tasty pizza.

Gattara delivers delicious appetizers and pizzas, and breaks down the "hotel restaurant" stereotype.

Gattara, which means "cat lady," is a cat-themed Italian-American restaurant downtown, located next door to the Warwick Hotel. Yes, I did say "cat" themed! You can find adorable cats in artwork along the walls and even hidden elsewhere. The interior is very spacious, with high ceilings, with a calm, warm atmosphere. There's a bar and even a brunch bar with bottomless mimosas available on the weekends.

Now onto the food.... the pizzas are bomb. They offer creative, wood-fired, Neopolitan-style pizzas like the carbonara and prosciutto di parma pizzas. My favorite was definitely the prosciutto di parma, although the carbonara is worth a try as well. The prosciutto di parma comes with mascarpone, pecorino romano, arugula, and cured egg yolk. I'm pretty sure I've never had pizza elsewhere with egg yolk on top, but it was incredibly delicious! They also offer gluten-free pizza crusts, which is what we got. The gluten-free crust has the perfect chewy consistency and is made with gluten-free beer.

Besides the diverse selection of pizzas, they also offer fun seasonal ones. I had the opportunity to try the Thanksgiving pizza, which had cranberry orange puree, shaved acorn squash, brown sugar, mozarella, and turkey meat.

Now on to the appetizers... they have some very pretty (and delicious) shareable appetizers. My favorites would include the san marzano tomato focaccia, charred octopus, and the potato strata.

Besides the delicious pizzas (highly recommend that prosciutto di parma pizza!!), they have a super delectable oatmeal raisin cookie ice cream sandwich. I love ice cream (probably way too much), but this was vanilla ice cream with lavender sprinkled on top, sandwiched between two super chewy, thick cookies. Not only that, but it is served with a rich house-made caramel. Oh man, oh man, I'm craving it just by writing about it!

Gattara is a definite winner and worth checking out. It's charming for cat lovers, an excellent ladies' brunch spot, and great for a date night.

text:
This restaurant is fairly new, and took over the space where "Vietnamese Cuisine" used to be. I've been there a few times now, and it's becoming one of my favorites. The staff doesn't speak English fluently, but they speak enough to take your orders and requests. They're very nice people.

I was with a gal friend there once and ordered something I hadn't tried before. It was a giant tray of grilled meats for two. When they brought it out I went for it with my fork thinking we're just supposed to eat out of the tray. The server immediately stopped me, and showed me these round things that they also brought out, along with a giant bowl of water. Turns out those are rice noodle wraps, and we're supposed to get them wet, then make rolls out of them. He patiently showed us how to make awesome rice wrap rolls, and told us stories of how this was one of his family's tradition when they got together. We had a great time.

The quality of the food has been spot on every time, and if you have a request (my friend wanted her pork borderline burnt) they'll quickly comply.

text: This is an interesting concept with both Thai and Filipino food, Soypinoy,  under one roof (or stall). I, of course, had to try both! First, the Chicken Inasal was great! This is from the Soypinoy menu and I highly recommend it. I also wanted some spice so jumped on Waterfall Pork from the Thai Kun menu. I believe it was labeled quite spicy but I didn't notice too much of a kick. This dish is loaded with flavors though and maybe even... too much? By the end of it, the flavors I was tasting was just not pleasant. This may be a dish that is an acquired taste. But I look forward to exploring more of the menu next time!

name: chris f
text: Don’t bother. I was in the area for work and was craving a couple slices for lunch. I went in at noon and they didn’t even have any slices available and none on the way. The guy at the counter quickly described what was ready and I was in a hurry so I settled on a pre-made 4 meat calzone. Anything else would have taken 20 minutes to prepare. It seemed this guy was hell bent getting me out of the restaurant as quickly as possible. As I sat down to eat at the table and was rudely told that I couldn’t eat in the restaurant because the didn’t have their “certificate of occupancy”. Whatever. I ended up having to eat in my car and was very disappointed with the food. It had obviously been sitting for several hours, because the crust was very soggy and the inside watery and cold. This place doesn’t deserve my business and hopefully you won’t make the same mistake. I saw other negative reviews but unfortunately I didn’t heed the warnings. Life is too short for this kind of eating experience.

resp.text:
Hi Chris,

We are under new leadership and ownership! Same recipes, different attitude! We are striving to be nice! Going forward, when we are out of slices, we are going to try a new concept which is make another pie to make slices available! Please think about trying us again, you'll have a different experience.

Thanks,
Pecce's Team

name: Jeff G
text:
My original review here was for Primo's Pizza, which was purchased and is under new management as Pecce's.

I don't like that the new place inherits reviews from the old. I'd have raved about Primo's (former review was 5-stars), but know little of the new store or management.

The new menu list seems a bit juvenile (really? The "tight seal" pizza? Because it plugs you up? Ugh...), and that's my only current experience with the place. I'm not a big fan of the new menu items so haven't ordered anything. I've changed this to a neutral 3-star review because of this.

resp.text:
Hi Jeff,
Sorry you have concerns about the menu, but as we’ve said in our “about us” everything is based on my family. Pecce is my mother’s maiden name. My maternal grandmother is our logo. All of the names of items on the menu came from significant people or events in my family.

Thanks for the feedback. Hope this explains more about the menu. If you have any questions in the future, please feel free to ask us directly!

PP

text: I cannot believe how amazing this place is and how off base some of these reviews are. I was working a 14 hour graveyard shift about a mile away from here and got very hungry around 7PM. I found them online having never ate here before, and noticed they were closing soon. So I called for delivery, hoping they could make change for a $100 bill, which was all the money I had on me. Even though drivers aren't supposed to carry that much, the amazing woman taking my order figured it out for me and got my order to me within an hour, even delivering after they closed and the food was still piping hot. She absolutely saved my night and I'm truly impressed by the effort made to satisfy a first time customer. I ordered a suprimo calzone, a chicken parmesan sandwich, and ravioli, and everything was phenomenal. The portions were huge, especially the calzone, and the size of the ravioli along with the huge amount of sausage in the dish was well worth it. The garlic twist that came with the ravioli was flaky and warm deliciousness. The marinara was amazing. This was honestly the best Italian food I've ever had. Worth every penny and the service is worth a good tip. While the wait can seem long as some others complain about, I'd say it's absolutely worth the wait, and you can always order an hour or two before you plan to eat. Shouts out and thank you to the crew of Primo's for an amazing meal that got me through the long night, I will definitely be a repeat customer.

resp.text:
Mason,

Thank you for taking the time to write this review. Your feedback is extremely important to us and we greatly value your opinion. We understand that you have a lot of options and choices in the area and we appreciate the fact that we were able to earn your business. (Should Primo's know they had an issue, assuming that was not their normal crust, I would be willing to try a pizza on the house. That is assuming, you value your customers. Otherwise, we will go elsewhere.) Also the sides of sauce for the calzone tasted like it contained hot sauce. Odd.... I know garlic can be spicy, and there was garlic in the sauce, however, our sauce had a kick that was beyond garlic!! It was ok, but I love spicy so I didnt mind. My husband, on the other hand, could not eat it. Do want to mention the girl that took the phone order and delivery guy were both very nice. The delivery guy even thanked me for checking them out. Too bad that alone is not enough.

resp.text:
I could not wait to finally have time to respond to this review. Let me start out by saying that we are a very small shop that tends to get very busy. We told you up front that your delivery time would exceed 90 minutes and you were quite alright with that on the phone. In addition to that, you requested to have a crispy crust, which I said, would make your pizza very dry. Apparently that was not an issue for you until you received your order (the rest of our conversation, to save you some embarrassment, I will just leave out). In the end, we realized that there are just some people that are not worth wasting time on.

On a side note, because of you, we no longer do "CRISPY" crust. We would like to wish you a happy 2018.

The Primo's Team

name: Austin Scott
text: Mark is one of the most-dedicated sushi chefs in Denver, and he makes sure the food is prepared and served the way he knows it's right. Many come just for the bi bim bob. The sushi is fantastic. There is a nice selection of hot and cold sake. It's a cozy little place about the size of what you might expect a small coffee shop or deli to be. Go across the street to Pablo's for delicious coffee and pastries afterward, or treat yourself to Mark's green tea ice cream or his must-try ice cream tempura!

text: Got the baja shrimp tacos. Ridiculously long wait for 3 SOGGY tacos. The slaw on them was just an absolute soupy mess, dripping everywhere. It should have been somewhat drained before plopping them on the tortillas. I haven't been so unsatisfied with a meal in a while. When you spend your hard earned money, you expect a certain level of satisfaction. Don't waste your money here.

name: G P
text:
The Denver Central Market is a gourmet marketplace and food hall. This food hall sits right in the middle of the Rino neighborhood, and has a nice variety of stuff to choose from (pizza, sandwiches, seafood, sandwiches, to name a few), as well a full bar.

Tammen's Fish is a full-service fish market inside Central Market. Walking through the front doors of the Denver Central Market, the first thing you'll see is Tammen's seafood counter. Got some oysters and was pretty good, service was friendly and efficient.

name: Eli Citron
text: I work there great food honestly. Fish tostadas  are fantastic. Always recommend

name: Mike Looney
text: Tremendous fish market--hands down the best in Denver. Jesus Silva (owner) is extremely knowledgeable and seems to have a recipe for everything I buy. Top quality fish not too pricey and a bomb happy hour!!

name: Kendra Sand
text: My ceviche here was terrible. They served it covered in a cream sauce and when I asked about it they said it was “Caribbean style.” I lived in the Caribbean for most of my childhood and never had ceviche in anything but lime juice. (They didn’t have a great attitude when I questioned it.) The quality of the fish was not good and the ceviche was flavorless. They also served it with bottom-of-the-bag broken up chips. I won’t eat here again but perhaps the oysters are good.

name: Ralph Gray
text: Really delicious, fresh poke at a great price! The staff are friendly and funny which is a nice perk too.

name: Steve Replogle
text:
I stopped in here on Martin Luther King Junior Day, as the people were forming into little groups to wait for the Marade to come by. I was given a friendly greeting by the young woman puttering around busily behind the counter. Four or five other people sat around the quaint, comfortable premises - talking, reading, sipping hot drinks and nibbling on breakfast goodies.

There were many appetizing choices on offer, but I simply ordered a cup of hot chocolate. After a few moments, it was all prepared, and I sat down in a nice old chair with my cup.

I don’t know why or how, but it was the BEST cup of hot chocolate I’ve had in years. The best!

I must go to back to this little shop. That hot chocolate was so very good that I will order other items, next time - perhaps one of everything!

resp.text: Steve, thank you so much for your thoughtful and immensely kind review! We look very forward to seeing you again, and hope you have a great rest of your week!

name: Gabriel Fonseca
text: I have to admit that the place looks very clean.  Neat idea having multiple types of dishes under one roof in a Buffet environment.  But.....   After being seated by a polite lady, I proceeded to the buffet where I picked up an egg roll, some fried rice, Beef and Broccoli and a ham cake.   Tasted ok, nothing spectacular but I do have to admit that the food wasn't very warm.  I guess after 2 bites I should have known better but I was hungry and wasn't thinking properly about food safety.   While sitting there eating I also noticed that people were adding new food to old food on the buffet.  I guess I really didnt think anything of that either.  (Little did I know at the time this is a health department violation)  After finishing my first plate I went back to the buffet and picked up a different type of eggroll looking thing, I think it was called a Vietnam roll or something of the sorts, a piece of red colored chicken on a skewer, and a couple pieces of what looked like coconut shrimp.   After biting into the roll thing which was barely warm and mushy inside and had the texture of cat food I immediately put it down and asked the waitress lady if she could take the temperature of the food on the buffet.  I freaked out when she finally found a thermometer and shoved it into a roll and it registered at 104 degrees farenheit... Oh crap...   while she was doing this I noticed that the cold items area was also not very cold.  Glad I didn't get anything from the dessert area....   I asked for a refund based on unsanitary food conditions.  Hot food needs to be kept at or over 140 and cold foods at 40 or under or you can make people VERY SICK.    The waitress kindly notified me that the steam table was malfunctioning.   Shouldn't they have just taken all the food off and not used that buffet line?  Or am I freakin insane ?

name: Daniel Shannon
text: We've eaten at Il Posto many times since  it opened and have never been disappointed. Andreas, the owner is a perfectionist and it shows. He is a great host and his staff is always very, very welcoming. The food is excellent, on par with the (other) very best restaurants in Denver.  He uses the finest and freshest  ingredients and cooks them to perfection. The wine list is excellent, and the somm has invariably been very helpful and spot on with his recommendations. The restaurant isn't large, but it has a great, lively, comfortable atmosphere. The risotto is fantastic, as are all of the pasta dishes. The menu changes frequently, and it is always interesting. The waitstaff are unobtrusive but attentive. Dani has waited on us several times, and she does a great job.  I recommend Il Posto without reservation!

name: D T
text: By far my favorite Italian restaurant in Denver. Cher Andrea is amazing, and cooking lessons with him are a must if you like authentic risotto or gnocchi. The menu has a couple of dishes which are always available, but  there is something new and different every time you go there. I had some of the best desserts ever - they have their own pastry chef  and she makes everything from scratch. I really hope that the 17th street location will be remodeled and open again. I am yet to try the downtown location.

name: Kevin Triolo
text: Some of the best Italian in Denver. Excellent pasta made in house daily. Very cool and relaxing atomosphere while remaining classy enough to impress a date. Friendly and knowledgeable wait staff. Also dig the open kitchen.

name: Neil Robertson
text: As the menu changes daily, I am always pleasantly surprised. I've never had a bad thing or even a decent thing here. It is always exceptional. It has also been one of my favorite places to recommend to friends when looking for a special place to go and they have never less than raved about their experience as well.

name: Sergey Dremin
text: As some of the other reviews indicate, the portions are very small for what you are paying and the quality is also lacking for this level. We dropped $200 for two people and walked away almost hungry. It gets pretty ridiculous with some dishes, like the 4 scallops they served on a giant peace of marble, neatly arranged on one side of the marble block, leaving 3/4 of the area empty. It was listed as a main course, but did not come with any carbs or salad to complement the scallops. The scallops themselves should have been cooked perfectly for that price, instead they were fried for the same amount of time, the two bigger pieces being very good, but the two smaller ones being overcooked, and who really wants to eat overcooked scallops? We also got some flavorful, but under-cooked, risotto. And when we sent it back, instead of making a new batch, they just reheated what remained on the plate. How much did I pay for this again? The bread served at the beginning of the meal came out of a fridge, it would be nicer if it were warm. On the plus side, the decor is great, but a little crowded. The cheese platter was very unique and totally worth it.

name: Debra Zinik
text: What happened to this place?  It used to be so good.  The presentation of our appetizer was horrible.  The first course was tasteless and the main courses were bland, a first grader must be mixing corn and pasta putting it on a slate slab.  It was so disappointing on every level.  Even dessert was a flop.  At $100/person this place needs to step it up or die.  It was really really bad.

name: Cooper Boeke
text:
Made a reservation, be aware that a reservation for two people means you are getting seated at a community table or the bar. do not use this for a first date place unless you feel like being elbow to elbow with random people.

The food, no idea. When they told me they were converting all the two tops for a group that showed up I didn't bother and found another place.

Very limited menu, which is okay for the size of the resturant/ location. The decor and resturant table setting was wonderful. Overall, the food was overpriced and not great. (Could have been an off day).

name: Tristan Copley Smith
text: ABSOLUTELY DELICIOUS. An evening of luxury, for not much money at all. Lovely staff, scrumptious wine and food.....you really can't go wrong with Il Posto.

name: Denver Runner
text: Great Italian place, but personally think it's way over priced. I like how creative the menu is and that it changes daily, but you pay for it. The pasta I got was very good don't get me wrong, but very small portion for the price. We got a bottle of wine (nothing fancy), a salad to share, and 2 pasta dishes and spent over $100. Personally I think it's a little much for what you get. The decor however is amazing and I loved the vibe. Beware though the tables are very close together so if you don't want people hearing your convo, not a good place to go. All in all, mixed emotions and not worth it unless you're looking for a fancy fun night out then it's perfect.

name: John Hunter Houser
text: Very nice pasta dishes with an up scale Italian feel.

name: Gregg Cassarini
text: Great food, great service, great atmosphere. Need I say more

name: john koelling
text: Good food. Pretending to be upscale.

name: Jami M. Guler
text: Great Happy Hour and Wine selection

name: Chad Walz
text: Have been multiple times of the years. Great people and food.

name: Josh Gipper
text: My favorite restaurant in Denver, it always surprises.

name: Andrea Padula
text: very nice place!!! very modern cuisine!!!always nice to come here!!love this place!!

name: Lauren A.
text: Excellent Italian food.

name: Kaz
text: I love this bar!! As a huge horror movie fanatic and lover of all Halloween decor this place is my go-to spot from now on. The bartenders are always awesome and the atmosphere is so laid back and super fun.

name: lizzie leitz
text: This venue is off to a great start - but has a long way to go. The staff was phenomenal, very personal and knowledgeable. As a longtime horror lover, I expected more from the decor: there was horror paraphernalia everywhere but the overall vibe (furniture, walls, etc.) was more or less like any other bar. There were lots of screens with different horror movies playing, but most with no subtitles or sound. The seating was disappointing, our "table for 3" was three chairs crowded around a bedside-table type setup. During covid is surely a difficult time to start a theme bar like this, I look forward to seeing what they make of it down the road!

resp.text: Hey Lizzie! Thanks for reaching out. We feel you on this one. We are a new bar trying a unique concept in the middle of a global pandemic. We're working with what we got.  Also, the entire layout is extremely temporary because we are hoping that in the future we can seat more people more comfortably. Cheers!

name: Laura Salter
text: We had such a fun time here! Worth the 15-20 minute wait to get in on a friday night. Great drinks, great service, they did a super fun give away, watched a great movie and there was an awesome community atmosphere. I want to make this one of our regular haunts!!

name: Jason Arment
text: It's a great a bar. The staff is nice. The service is pretty quick if you aren't shy about ordering a drink. Right now (4/25/2021) there is a wait to get in the bar because it's the new place to be. I genuinely like the way this place is an intersection of subculture and cinema.

name: Kai Gomez
text: Cool place, nice drinks love the decor but the movies are just a bit too loud especially with the amount of screaming in horror movies. I would enjoy this place so much more if it was a little quieter, cant even hear my own voice

name: Katie Knull
text: We love this place. Tons of fun. Will need to come back for movie night and Halloween!

resp.text: Appreciate the kindness! And we're just excited for Halloween as you are!

name: Kaite O'Leary
text: Really sad how big of a let down this bar was. I've been looking forward to going for a hot minute and finally decided today was the day. Arrived 15 minutes after open and there was a significant line. There isn't a bouncer or door man outside constantly so, people are cutting in line. The movies are a nice idea but, I think that should be a ticketed event. There's not a successful system for them to handle their popularity. Clearly understaffed which is 100% a management issue.The door man that did come out was lovely. Very fun and personable. After waiting about an hour and a half I gave up.I think they have a great concept and I still would like to but, they need to hire people and figure out a better waitlist or reservation system.

resp.text: Hey there! We absolutely agree with you in this. We opened as a small bar not thinking we were going to be as popular as we have been. We are trying our best to hire and manage the place but even with a door guy or more employees, the place is still a small bar. We are already planning expansion but things take time. Also with our licensing we are not allowed to sell tickets for the films. I see where you are coming from with your ideas and you are not alone with these, but we are just doing to best we can as a small new business. Thanks for the feed back.

name: Jo Py
text: Small bar with great drinks and music! They are a pretty new bar, so they're still getting the swing of things down. Once we were inside, we didn't have to wait long for our drinks. The line to get in was pretty long. We arrived at 4:30. We were second in line for their 5pm opening on a weekend. Other people had to wait much longer to enter. The decor is super fun, the drinks are horror themed, and there's a cool photobooth inside. I loved watching the screening of the movie. Very fun atmosphere!

name: Steven Clark
text: Loved this place great atmosphere! Good movie! Tasty drinks and two awesome talented bartenders! One even told us about the inspiration behind our drinks! Great place handsome bartender good drinks amazing shots and horror movies what more could one want!!!

name: Alicia Martinez
text: Cool place to hang out, downside was that we did have to wait outside for a while before we could come in. Place is small but the drinks and music are good.

name: Tyler Wicklund
text: Waited over an hour and a half to get in. Watched 2 people taking up single seats get moved after 20 minutes while others got to hog the bar and couch for almost 2+ hours with nothing said to them. Management understaffed the place and ruined the experience. Would not recommend waisting the time or money. I don't blame the staff I blame the management. There needs to be more staff and a better regulation on how long peoe can be there for. I know covid I'd had but I've watched small local breweries and bards all over the city adapt to meet the restrictions and eamanss of their businesses. I was truly excited to go here but disappointed in the delivery.

resp.text: Sorry you had a lame time at Horror Bar. Not sure our style of establishment was what you were looking for. Thanks for checking us out at least! Hope you have a great rest of the evening.

name: Alyssa Burhop
text: A lil pricey but for the most part was a great experience

name: Tanner
text:
Rude bartenders, walked in with my service dog and got told they don't allow dogs until I told her he was a service animal than I was told they're at compacity for the night when there were clearly bar stools and 2 booths open.

Re: When I had gone there was two black couches/booths open on the left side of the building along the wall which are pictured in the pictures uploaded on Google of the  bar. And I also find it funny that we were told there wasn't any manager on duty when we asked the bartender if we could speak to one. The only thing about horror in this bar is the experience. If your looking for legitimate drinks with class and awesome showcase to them go to adrift or Welton room.

resp.text: Hey there Tanner. I am the owner and I was there when you came in with your dog. Monday we were currently full and on a wait from the moment we opened until the moment we closed which isn't uncommon for us. Not exactly sure what you thought you saw but we limit bar seating with 6 feet of space between parties due to Covid 19 restrictions set by the CDC and the state of Colorado and we also don't have booths at Horror Bar. Hope you have a great day!

name: Sterling Yepiz-Cook
text:
I don’t want to hype this place up because it already forms a line at opening, but...

It’s my favorite place to invest money in a future hangover. They play some deep cuts (Sleepaway Camp 2, anyone) and great music. The guys that run the place have an incredible knowledge of mixology. I’ve drank the menu by now and everything they served was wildly unique and delicious. If I ever see that stimulus check, I’m spending it here.

name: Jameson Schryer
text: Great drinks and amazing movie selection. The staff is passionate about horror movies, and has a great deal of knowledge.

name: Neil Guzman
text: Had a blast and the staff were super friendly and accommodating. Awesome vibe and great movies always showing. Cannot wait to go back.

name: Rance Fredericksen
text: Super fun if you're into cult classics and horror movies!! Great staff and fun atmosphere for a little place!! Kudos!

name: Efrosini Krokos
text:
Terrible bar and service, the bartender with the heavy makeup was unhelpful and disgusting as was the male bartender. Denied me service, a 22 year old, all because I forgot an ID in Foco and they didn't want to trust official government records like my school records and such. Disgusting. Not even decorated. Never coming back. Foco has a better bar, R, that you should make the trip for. Not this mess.
Update: Bruh thanks for the snarky remark, you're both terrible at customer service and communication. Next time, don't talk to me.

resp.text: Hey there! I'll start by saying school records are not a valid form of ID that we except at our bar. Thanks for coming through though.

text: The drinks are great. Some of the best drinks I’ve had in a while. The Frankenstein wall decor was my fav, that I saw. The woman bartender is nice. The guy he tries to be personable to certain ppl and I thought that was a bit lame. My sister and I came waited for over an hour apparently we were the only ones in the long waiting group who didn’t receive a sticker? Idk but it’s definitely a cool experience. Cool concept. I think it will be so great during the summer. The only bad thing is the long wait.

text: Fantastic fresh food, they will build to suit--literally anything, just ask.  The green chili is perfectly spicy on breakfast burritos. Great portions & prices!

name: Brad Bedford
text:
Large variety of Asian, grill (hamburgers/fries etc), fresh sandwhiches and salads.

There are like 4 different lines depending on which of the four you want to go with, but ask one of the friendly staff and they'll help you out.

There is also a special of the day that is usually a good deal.

They also have REALLY good breakfast burritos for like $5. Something nice and hot to start the day is great.

I recommend it for lunch or breakfast to any new member of the office.

There might be a line, but the food comes out very quick! I don't think I've ever spent more than 10 minutes in there if I wasn't eating in the restaurant.

text: This market is a shadow of its former self, and not just because of COVID. There are fewer than a dozen vendors, and about the same number of customers. One produce farmer, one peaches and plums vendor, one bakery, a knife vendor... And no food on site, no restrooms.

resp.text: Not sure what market you went to but the Cherry Creek Fresh Market on Saturdays is large, vibrant and well attended with many wonderful local vendors. Please visit 😀
